At 06:44 AM 16/11/01, you wrote:
&gt;Hi
&gt;Thanks for the detailed reply.
&gt;
&gt;Can you help me out on the second question .. How do I write test cases 
for
&gt;event driven program ?
&gt;For e.g. I have a class A.
&gt;This has three functions
&gt;1. public boolean ConnectURL();
&gt;This function connects to a particular URL and loads the details onto the
&gt;screen. If this is successful, it returns true else false.
&gt;2. public void Initialisation();
&gt;This functions initializes some parameters
&gt;3. public boolean Save(Object obj);
&gt;This function saves the details on the screen and if successful, it 
returns
&gt;true, else false.

Yuk! Horrible naming - the customary naming convention is for lowercase
method names. (There&#39;s a pdf on sun&#39;s customary coding conventions - you
can download it from Sun).



&gt;  In my test class, I will be writing test methods for all these 
functions.
&gt;1. Do I need to write a test method for the second function that is just
&gt;doing some initialization. If so, how will I write that ?

You should definitely test the initialisation - assuming it actually does
something &quot;interesting&quot;. You might find that you need to add some get/set
methods to do so, though.


&gt;2. For the first function, I will write a test method as follows
&gt;public boolean testConnectURl() {
&gt;         A obj1;
&gt;         boolean  b = obj1.ConnectURL();
&gt;         /// How do I write an assert statement after this ?
&gt;}


assertTrue(&quot;Connection failed?&quot;, b);

or

URL myURL = objl.getURL();
// connect, test content a la httpunit.



&gt;I have seen the archive of all the messages but I am not clear on how I
&gt;write test classes for event driven programs.


The same as any other way. Don&#39;t forget that unit testing is not about
testing program flow - it&#39;s about testing how a class works at a &quot;unit&quot;
level. This is (often) taken to mean testing methods/functions.










